WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.600
Hi, my name is Sadeaka Watson, and so that's me.

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:17.480
I work as a data scientist at Eli Lilly, the pharmaceutical company.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:22.639
I'm on the development team for a Shiny application that is used at Lilly.

00:00:22.639 --> 00:00:29.000
So essentially my job is to wear this hat, the app developer hat.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.840
This isn't just a normal Shiny app.

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:33.799
This is a complex production-grade app.

00:00:33.799 --> 00:00:37.040
We get a new version of the app released every month

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:39.400
with new features and bug fixes.

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:41.320
And a lot of people in my organization

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:43.720
visit this app every day, so it's really important

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:47.240
that the app is functioning properly all the time.

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:49.599
So with that in mind, I'd like to begin with a story

00:00:49.599 --> 00:00:53.320
about something that happened to me back in May 2021.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:57.119
So I was in my home office working on a new feature for the app,

00:00:57.119 --> 00:01:00.599
but of course I was multitasking because I was also keeping an eye

00:01:00.599 --> 00:01:03.200
on the activity in our team chat window.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:07.559
So one of the users was saying she was having some issues with the app.

00:01:07.559 --> 00:01:11.720
It wasn't populating the drop-down menu with the values that she was expecting.

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:13.879
So the values were in the app before,

00:01:13.879 --> 00:01:16.519
and then now all of a sudden she didn't see them anymore.

00:01:16.519 --> 00:01:21.040
So one of the other developers identified the issue

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:24.919
and determined that we would have to quickly release a new version of the app

00:01:24.919 --> 00:01:28.239
that resolves the issue with the drop-down menu.

00:01:28.239 --> 00:01:30.599
And that's when I panicked because I realized

00:01:30.599 --> 00:01:34.480
that meant two things were about to happen.

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:40.599
First, it meant that I would have to put on another hat,

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:41.919
my code reviewer hat.

00:01:41.919 --> 00:01:46.160
So as a code reviewer, I'm responsible for reviewing GitHub pull requests,

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:49.959
have to read the code to make sure it adheres to our coding standards,

00:01:49.959 --> 00:01:52.080
and then I have to run the app in a local environment

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:55.839
to make sure that all the old features work with the new features.

00:01:55.839 --> 00:01:58.800
I have to check the radio buttons, the drop-down menus,

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:00.800
the contents of the tables.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:04.519
I have to make sure that the database API and the model API connections

00:02:04.519 --> 00:02:08.639
are still working as they used to as we added these new features.

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:13.800
And so if it passes those tests, then we deploy the app to the test server.

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:17.759
But then that means I have to put on yet another hat.

00:02:17.759 --> 00:02:20.520
This time I have to put on my app tester hat.

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:22.880
So as a member of the app testing team,

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:28.759
I was one of several people that had to manually

00:02:28.759 --> 00:02:30.960
test the deployed version of the app.

00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:33.639
So I would have to open the app in a web browser

00:02:33.639 --> 00:02:35.559
and then run a lot of the same tests as before,

00:02:35.559 --> 00:02:38.399
check the radio buttons, check the drop-down menus,

00:02:38.399 --> 00:02:40.880
check the API connections, database connections,

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:44.320
all those other things that I did before in the code review.

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:46.160
And so now the only difference is that this

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:48.160
is on the deployed version of the app as opposed

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:50.759
to the pre-deployment version.

00:02:50.759 --> 00:02:52.279
Now, testing is very important.

00:02:52.279 --> 00:02:55.639
It does allow us to catch bugs so that we can fix them

00:02:55.639 --> 00:02:59.880
before the new version of the app is released to production.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:03.559
However, as one of the people who was responsible for actually

00:03:03.559 --> 00:03:05.800
running the test, I could say that this

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:11.199
was a really extremely tedious, painful experience for me.

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:13.360
It was very stressful.

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:15.919
I also felt undervalued because I'm thinking,

00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:19.940
OK, I have a PhD in statistics, and yet my job now

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:23.600
is to click this radio button or check this drop-down menu.

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:26.839
So I felt like this wasn't a good use of my time.

00:03:26.839 --> 00:03:29.960
Another issue is that I and the other app testers

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:31.080
had other priorities.

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:33.039
So we weren't full-time app testers.

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:35.279
We could only run the test when we

00:03:35.279 --> 00:03:37.919
had time to squeeze testing in.

00:03:37.919 --> 00:03:41.479
And that meant that managing all of those schedules

00:03:41.479 --> 00:03:42.919
across the different testers meant

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:44.839
that it could take a long time for us

00:03:44.839 --> 00:03:47.339
to get through those tests and actually go to the next stage

00:03:47.339 --> 00:03:50.639
of our software release.

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:52.960
So that was increasing the amount of time

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:55.440
it took us to deploy the app.

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:56.960
Because it was so time-intensive,

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:59.320
we had to sparingly apply these tests.

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:00.919
So we couldn't afford to run them

00:04:00.919 --> 00:04:02.479
as new features were coming in.

00:04:02.479 --> 00:04:04.800
We had to use multiple scenarios.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:09.160
We could only do them really once if we could do that.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:12.199
And then lastly, we found that different testers were

00:04:12.199 --> 00:04:16.279
running the tests with slightly different conditions.

00:04:16.279 --> 00:04:18.959
So there was some subjective assessment

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:21.799
with whether or not the test passed or failed.

00:04:21.799 --> 00:04:23.399
So one tester could say it passed,

00:04:23.399 --> 00:04:25.079
and another person running the same test

00:04:25.079 --> 00:04:26.440
would say that it failed.

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:28.640
So that was a problem.

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:31.160
So because these releases were such a heavy burden for me,

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:34.200
I started looking for a way to make this process more

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:36.579
efficient for me and for our team.

00:04:36.579 --> 00:04:38.640
I was already familiar with Selenium.

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:41.040
I knew it was a great tool for automating interactions

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:42.440
with the web browser.

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:44.559
And I figured this might help automatically check

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:46.640
whether the UI elements were still

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:49.359
working on the deployed version of the app.

00:04:49.359 --> 00:04:52.760
I was somewhat familiar with the rvest package

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:54.480
and that it was great for web scraping.

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:57.179
So I figured this might help to programmatically extract

00:04:57.179 --> 00:04:59.079
the contents of the web page.

00:04:59.079 --> 00:05:00.519
And I could run some sanity checks

00:05:00.519 --> 00:05:02.160
against it to make sure everything's rendering

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:04.559
properly so Selenium and rvest could work together

00:05:04.559 --> 00:05:07.320
on the deployed version of the app.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:09.679
My colleague Eric Nant recommended

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:12.000
that I use the Shinytest package

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.799
to test the code that other developers were submitting

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:16.559
in their pull requests.

00:05:16.559 --> 00:05:19.079
So he figured that that might help to automate

00:05:19.079 --> 00:05:21.040
some of the code reviews.

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:22.600
And then, of course, later I found out

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:26.000
that there was another version of the Shinytest package

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.839
called Shinytest2 that somebody will speak about later.

00:05:29.839 --> 00:05:32.399
And then finally, the Shinytest documentation

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:36.559
was recommending that we also use the test that package.

00:05:36.559 --> 00:05:39.000
And so now I had all these tools.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.440
There was a bit of a learning curve,

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:42.160
but I took about three months of my time.

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:44.440
And eventually, over the next three months,

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:48.279
I was able to use those tools to create an automated testing

00:05:48.279 --> 00:05:50.440
pipeline.

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:53.399
Let's see how the software release workflow changed

00:05:53.399 --> 00:05:57.000
after introducing these tools.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.959
So in the code review stage in blue,

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:04.480
we see the manual pre-deployment testing during code reviews

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:07.559
was replaced with the Shinytest2 script that

00:06:07.559 --> 00:06:09.320
automates these same tasks.

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:11.320
And now the code reviewer hat sits

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:15.359
on the head of the bot that runs the test script.

00:06:15.359 --> 00:06:19.920
And then in orange, in the post-deployment testing stage,

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:24.239
I'm running the manual regression test.

00:06:24.239 --> 00:06:27.600
I'm replacing those with a suite of Selenium test scripts.

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:29.920
And then I get to remove that heavy app tester hat

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:31.640
from my head and place it on the bot who

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:33.640
is happy to run those test scripts.

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:36.200
At least he doesn't complain about it if he does not

00:06:36.279 --> 00:06:38.239
feel happy about it.

00:06:38.239 --> 00:06:40.760
So those two changes had a significant impact

00:06:40.760 --> 00:06:42.880
on our software release workflow.

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:46.920
Our code reviewers and app testers had less work to do.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:49.320
They weren't feeling stressed out with each new release.

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:52.040
We didn't have to worry about testers balancing their testing

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:53.640
duties with other high-priority work,

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.399
so we ended up shortening our time to deployment

00:06:56.399 --> 00:07:00.959
from five days to five hours, which was pretty

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:03.040
huge for our testing team.

00:07:03.079 --> 00:07:06.600
We could apply our testing criteria as often as needed.

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:09.640
So no matter how many releases we had during the month

00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:14.959
or feature pull requests that we merged during the month.

00:07:14.959 --> 00:07:17.679
And then because the test logic was contained in the test

00:07:17.679 --> 00:07:22.000
script, that meant we could consistently apply that test

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.760
logic from one test run to the next

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:27.839
so that removed that variation in test results

00:07:27.839 --> 00:07:30.119
that we were looking for.

00:07:30.119 --> 00:07:32.600
So I've talked about this before on the previous slides,

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:34.440
but here's where I get to formally introduce

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:38.040
the automated testing pipeline that I'm proposing.

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:40.000
It contains four key principles.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.279
First, I believe you should automate the tests.

00:07:43.279 --> 00:07:45.239
You should actually have some sort of programmatic

00:07:45.239 --> 00:07:48.760
representation of your test logic.

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:51.480
And this could obviously be, we could easily

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:53.600
fill an hour or maybe a day talking about this,

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:55.519
but lots of different things like how do you

00:07:55.519 --> 00:07:56.959
recover safely from errors?

00:07:56.959 --> 00:07:59.119
How do you appropriately log the test results?

00:07:59.119 --> 00:08:01.679
How do you have this repository of all your test artifacts,

00:08:01.679 --> 00:08:03.519
maybe your screenshots or things

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:06.440
that were downloaded in the course of running the app?

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:09.480
That's what I mean by automating the test, all of that.

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:13.920
Next, it's important to have one or more development servers

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.839
that are completely separate from your production server.

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:19.399
And that allows us to see how the updated app works

00:08:19.399 --> 00:08:22.399
without breaking the production version that end users

00:08:22.399 --> 00:08:23.880
are interacting with.

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.839
And then the next two principles have

00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:28.320
to do with when we would run the test.

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:31.320
The first is that I recommend running

00:08:31.359 --> 00:08:33.799
some pre-deployment tests so that you can integrate

00:08:33.799 --> 00:08:37.599
these features safely in a safe space on your development

00:08:37.599 --> 00:08:39.919
server without crashing the version of your app

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:42.159
that the end users are using.

00:08:42.159 --> 00:08:44.880
And then finally, I would recommend

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:48.960
running the post-deployment check also

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:50.440
on the development server.

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:52.640
And this is where we can more closely mimic

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:54.960
what the end users are going to experience when they log

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:57.679
into the app using the web browser.

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:00.159
So again, pre-deployment and post-deployment,

00:09:00.159 --> 00:09:02.840
that's really important.

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:05.000
One question that comes up is whether automation

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.679
makes sense for a particular use case or a particular web app.

00:09:08.679 --> 00:09:12.359
And to answer this question, I usually

00:09:12.359 --> 00:09:14.599
follow up with a couple of follow-up questions.

00:09:14.599 --> 00:09:18.000
The first would be, is the logic consistent?

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.679
The test logic, is it consistent from one run to the next?

00:09:22.679 --> 00:09:25.440
So if you can say, step one, step two, step three,

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:28.840
if you can actually have all of that logic

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:31.840
and not have to worry about a change from one to the next,

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:33.239
that's one consideration.

00:09:33.239 --> 00:09:35.719
And then the second question would be

00:09:35.719 --> 00:09:38.400
whether the test logic can be completely scripted

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:40.320
so that you can get the result without having

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:41.840
to use any sort of subjective judgment

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:44.799
or having some sort of human involved making that decision.

00:09:44.799 --> 00:09:46.520
There are other considerations, obviously.

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:48.299
So there's, do you have the infrastructure

00:09:48.299 --> 00:09:50.640
to support these automation tools like Shiny Test 2

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:52.039
or Selenium?

00:09:52.039 --> 00:09:53.640
Do you have time to do this?

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:55.359
There's a little bit of a learning curve

00:09:55.359 --> 00:09:56.820
and a little bit of time investment

00:09:56.820 --> 00:09:58.760
in terms of writing these test scripts.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:00.340
But in general, I would say if you answered yes

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:01.919
to both of those questions, then I

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:04.640
would say your app is a prime candidate for automation.

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:11.640
So I prepared a working example that you can play around

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:12.679
with on your own.

00:10:12.679 --> 00:10:15.280
It's a simple app that allows you to create an ice cream

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:18.719
recipe using various ingredients like peanuts and raisins

00:10:18.719 --> 00:10:19.880
and chocolate syrup.

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:21.400
And for the adventurous, if you want

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:24.280
to add some chicken nuggets to your ice cream,

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:27.200
no judgment here, but we allow you to do that.

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:31.000
So the GitHub repo linked at the bottom

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:32.760
has all the code needed to run the app.

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:35.840
It also has the Shiny Test 2 and the Selenium code

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:37.799
that will allow you to just kind of play around

00:10:37.799 --> 00:10:39.179
with this in your own environment.

00:10:39.179 --> 00:10:42.280
So I definitely encourage you to check it out.

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:43.840
I created a couple of screencasts

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:45.719
that demonstrate how this would work.

00:10:45.719 --> 00:10:47.760
So first, I'll show you the pre-deployment testing

00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:50.119
with Shiny Test 2.

00:10:50.119 --> 00:10:52.280
Now, if you're running the Shiny Test

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:55.880
script in the RStudio IDE, I'll pause this.

00:10:55.880 --> 00:10:58.159
First, you'll see that there's a Run Test button visible

00:10:58.159 --> 00:10:59.640
at the top of the script.

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:01.880
And if you click that, you'll see

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:03.760
that there's some activity happening over here

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:07.640
in the Build tab that shows the progress of the test run.

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:09.440
This test script automatically opens up

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:12.960
this local version of the app in a web browser window.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:13.760
So I didn't do that.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:16.000
It did it on its own in Google Chrome.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.080
And then you'll notice that it's selecting various checkboxes

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:21.460
and entering text in the text field

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:23.119
and doing all kinds of things and showing

00:11:23.119 --> 00:11:25.039
how the app is changing.

00:11:25.039 --> 00:11:27.320
So all of those things happened automatically.

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:30.719
And so when I go back to the RStudio IDE,

00:11:30.719 --> 00:11:32.799
I see that the test result folder now

00:11:32.799 --> 00:11:37.039
contains a few files that were saved in the test run.

00:11:37.039 --> 00:11:38.840
And if I click on one of those, I've

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:43.000
got some screenshots that show what the app looked

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:44.719
like at various points in the app.

00:11:44.719 --> 00:11:48.159
There's also this JSON file that shows

00:11:48.159 --> 00:11:50.159
the values of various elements in the UI

00:11:50.159 --> 00:11:53.039
as they were at the time that the snapshot was created.

00:11:53.039 --> 00:11:55.760
If you stick around for the next talk in this session,

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:57.340
you'll actually get a chance to see

00:11:57.340 --> 00:12:01.479
the package author of the ShinyTest2 developer

00:12:01.479 --> 00:12:03.320
give a presentation about ShinyTest2.

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:05.239
So I didn't spend a whole lot of time

00:12:05.239 --> 00:12:07.320
thinking about that for this presentation.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:09.280
But I highly recommend that you check that out.

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:12.080
And finally, I'll show you what the post-deployment version

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:15.559
of the testing looked like with Selenium.

00:12:15.559 --> 00:12:19.520
So as before, we click the Run Test button at the top.

00:12:19.599 --> 00:12:24.559
We will also see the test run progress in the Build tab

00:12:24.559 --> 00:12:26.280
in the upper right corner.

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:29.059
Now, before, we would actually open up automatically

00:12:29.059 --> 00:12:31.000
this web browser in Google Chrome.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.159
But this is a headless browser, so we don't actually

00:12:33.159 --> 00:12:34.640
have access to that browser.

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:36.640
Instead, it's just going to do it under the hood

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:41.159
and silently execute those test instructions that I provided.

00:12:41.159 --> 00:12:47.440
And so we'll just see the mouse that I can't see anymore

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:48.239
for some reason.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:55.119
Where are you, mouse?

00:12:55.119 --> 00:12:57.520
I see it on your side, but not my side for some reason.

00:13:04.520 --> 00:13:05.440
Give me mouse.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:07.239
OK, there we go.

00:13:07.239 --> 00:13:08.919
I'll pause that here.

00:13:08.919 --> 00:13:11.280
So what you saw, and unfortunately, I

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:13.880
wasn't able to narrate that while it was going,

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:16.320
while I was looking for my mouse,

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:22.159
was that it was showing you how it was actually programmatically

00:13:22.159 --> 00:13:23.320
running the script.

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:26.880
And then it captured some screenshots along the way

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:29.320
as it progressed through the various test scripts.

00:13:29.320 --> 00:13:31.559
And it also, in the log area, it let

00:13:31.559 --> 00:13:33.200
you know what was going on in the app.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:35.640
So at this point, it was selecting the flavor.

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:38.760
And another point, it was selecting the recipe name

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:40.719
and so on.

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:43.960
So this was all very easy and straightforward

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:46.400
thanks to the tools that some of the other developers

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:47.599
have created.

00:13:47.599 --> 00:13:49.719
So I thank them for that.

00:13:49.719 --> 00:13:51.679
So in closing, I'd like to re-emphasize

00:13:51.679 --> 00:13:54.239
that these tools really make automated testing more

00:13:54.239 --> 00:13:57.479
accessible to the general population of data scientists,

00:13:57.479 --> 00:14:01.640
especially people like me who don't have any formal training

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:04.960
in software engineering or software testing.

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:06.640
We're kind of expected to know a lot

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:09.280
and do a lot about a lot of different areas.

00:14:10.280 --> 00:14:13.679
But this makes that a lot easier for us to do.

00:14:13.679 --> 00:14:16.179
And then another thing that is out of scope for this talk,

00:14:16.179 --> 00:14:17.599
but I get asked this all the time

00:14:17.599 --> 00:14:20.200
when I give a presentation about automated testing,

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:22.719
how does this fit into the CI-CD pipeline?

00:14:22.719 --> 00:14:23.640
It definitely does.

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:26.159
And there's lots of tools that you can use to do that.

00:14:26.159 --> 00:14:29.119
In particular, for example, if you had GitHub Actions,

00:14:29.119 --> 00:14:32.159
you could programmatically run.

00:14:32.159 --> 00:14:33.960
So as a person submits their pull request,

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:36.760
you could programmatically run your tests

00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:38.960
on the pre-deployment version of the app,

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:42.440
merge the pull requests, deploy to the next test server,

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:44.320
and then actually programmatically run

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:47.000
that next set of scripts.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.799
So you can do a lot of these things very, very easy.

00:14:50.799 --> 00:14:53.799
So I'd like to thank my colleagues at Eli Lilly

00:14:53.799 --> 00:14:55.760
and the Design Hub Data Insights, Information

00:14:55.760 --> 00:14:58.599
and Digital Solutions, and the Statistical Innovation Center

00:14:58.599 --> 00:15:00.039
teams for their help.

00:15:00.039 --> 00:15:02.159
And I'd also like to thank Wardell Piquette

00:15:02.159 --> 00:15:05.200
at Piquette Studios for his help with the graphic design

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:06.780
in my presentation.

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:08.719
And here's my contact information.

00:15:08.719 --> 00:15:11.080
Feel free to reach out if you'd like to discuss anything.

00:15:11.080 --> 00:15:12.280
And I thank you for your time.

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:13.440
Thank you.

